description.narrative:
The Budget Monitoring Forum (FMO) is a platform for civil society organizations working in the area of national public finance management monitoring and its influence, among policy makers, in favor of increasing the budget for the basic social sectors. This platform has existed for approximately 9 years and has been an important actor in strengthening budgetary citizenship, in placing key sectors as a discussion agenda for policy makers and in monitoring the executive. It is via the FMO in which the CCD is a member, that the activity plan becomes operational. The FMO actively participates in the dialogue spaces available, both those created by civil society in general, by cooperation partners, as well as the few made available by the Government. Throughout the budget cycle, the Forum has engaged consistently with the Plan and Budget Commission (CPO), during hearings with the government, when discussing the Economic and Social Plan (PES) and the State Budget and when discussing the General State Account (CGE). During this period of existence, the platform has produced and published policy briefs, analyzes and positions that have been used as evidence in engagement with the Government and other stakeholders through debates and training on Open Budget, Budget Cycle and Budget Transparency in which members of parliament, cooperation partners and interested citizens are involved.
As main activities can be highlighted the follow:
# Public debt transparency, research and publication of position papers;
# Monitoring of national and international public debt servicepayments;
# Engagement and training of the Assembly of the Republic on the impact of public debt;
# Engagement, public awareness and training on the impact of corruption on development: curb corruption, reducing openings for the misuse of public funds;
# Monitoring and pressure on Justice, particularly the Public Prosecutor's Office, for the judgment of autonomous cases linked to the former presidential family in the context of hidden debts;
# Public mobilization for collective action and public support for the FMO;
# Continued action before the Court in South Africa for the extradition of the formerF inance Minister to USA;
And as main expected results:
# Improved public finance management;
# Criminal liability of the Actors who have harmed the State with hidden debts and the reversal of their assets in favor of the State;
# Hidden debts eliminated from public accounts;
# International financial system responsible for the damages caused to the Mozambican people.
# Public opinion mobilized against hidden and illegal debts.
